deck_description: Evol Deck 2024

deck_excerpt: EMERGENCY! and Rescue-Ace Preventer are finally out in Masterduel! Combined with Snake-Eye, this fire deck is nigh unstoppable!
deck_description:
Thanks to the selection pack "Nightmare Arrivals," EMERGENCY! and Rescue-Ace Preventer have (finally) made their appearance in Masterduel! Combined with Snake-Eye, this fire deck is nigh unstoppable. If you want to reach high levels on Masterduel ladder with a reliable deck that can either 1st or 2nd and can cram a ton of staples while being consistently powerful, Rescue-ACE is a good deck to play!
 
All fire decks that feature a level 1 fire starter has recieved an unbelievable power boost with the release of the "Snake-Eyes" cards from the "Ride Into the Future" pack in Masterduel! Not only is there enhanced consistency with the Snake-Eye and Diabellestar cards, the power ceiling of RESCUE-ACE has dramatically increased as well, since the new additions to the deck allow it to link spam like no tomorrow! Powerful link bosses like Heatsoul, Amblowhale and Promethean Princess are easily made with a singular Snake-Eyes Ash, on top of your Turbulence's 4 set backrow!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This deck features two sets of cards in it, RESCUE-ACE and Snake-Eye. A reduced RESCUE-ACE core is included because of the consistency boost the Snake-Eye cards give, and now they number 16 cards. 2 hydrant rather than 3 is used since the card can now be seached/summoned from deck with the Snake-Eye cards. 3 EMERGENCY! are included since they function as "emergency teleport" and are effectively 1-card playstarters. 4 Rescue-ACE spells/traps are included as targets for Turbulence to set from deck. REINFORCE! isn't included since the card seems fairly inconsequential compared to the other quick-play spells and traps. One for One is included since it's an additional copy of any level 1 fire you need summoned from deck. 
 
Thanks to the consistency boost from Snake-Eyes and Bonfire, a whopping 15 STAPLES is included in the strategy, including 14 handtraps (RESCUE-ACE Impulse is actually a handtrap!). This means you're always going to interrupt your opponent, no matter what turn it is! The usual "Maxx C" package is included so the pilot can win the Maxx C minigame.
 
Unlike earlier iterations of this deck, the Extra Deck is now used a lot since the Snake-Eye cards grant this deck immense link climb ability. Linkuriboh + Sunlight Wolf summon Heatsoul, I:P Masquera can be summoned from the backrow during your opponent's turn with Flamberge Dragon, etc. The Extra Deck is a toolbox for answers to specific game states. Since many monsters in the Extra Deck aren't required, they can be banish fodder for Pot of Prosperity. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Rescue-ACE functions as a control-centred midrange deck. Usually, the deck summons Turbulence, sets 4 spells/traps from the deck (two interruptions and two follow-up cards). Combined with the Snake-Eyes cards, this strategy has become much more aggressive since it is able to link climb quickly to Accesscode for an OTK. The hand also may have Rescue-ACE warriors that function as handtraps to net further advantage from deck, hand or GY. 
 
Here is the deck's main combo: 
 
Snake-Eyes Ash + Rescue-ACE Turbulence/Extender = 4 set Rescue-ACE spells/traps (interruption and follow-up) + Promethean Princess in GY (monster destruction) + Amblowhale (link-monster summon and 1 card destruction) + Heatsoul (draw 2) + follow-up for next turn in hand
  1. Normal summon Snake-Eye Ash. Search for Poplar from deck with Ash' effect.
  2. Activate Poplar's trigger effect in hand to special summon it to the field.
  3. Activate Poplar's trigger effect to search for Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eyes.
  4. Link away Poplar for Linkuriboh. Activate Poplar's trigger effect to place it in the backrow.
  5. Activate Snake-Eye Ash's effect to send itself and Poplar to the GY to summon from deck Flamberge Dragon.
  6. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to place Poplar in the backrow.
  7. Activate Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eyes sending Poplar to summon from deck RESCUE-ACE Hydrant. 
  8. Activate Hydrant's effect to search for a RESCUE-ACE Turbulence or extender from deck (either Attacker or Fire Engine). 
  9. Link away Hydrant  + Flamberge Dragon to link summon Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf.
  10. Flamberge Dragon's trigger effect activates to summon Poplar + Hydrant from the GY.
  11. Activate RESCUE-ACE extender's effect in the hand to summon itself. 
  12. Link away Hydrant + RESCUE-ACE extender + Linkuriboh to link summon Promethean Princess to the zone above Sunlight Wolf. 
  13. Sunlight Wolf's trigger effect recovers you any fire monster in the GY (You can recover Ash Blossom for example!)
  14. Activate Turbulence's effect to summon itself from the hand banishing in GY Hydrant + RESCUE-ACE extender.
  15. Activate Turbulence's effect to set 4 RESCUE-ACE spells/traps from deck. Typically, you'd set ALERT! (search), RESCUE! (monster reborn), EXTINGUISH! (destroy monster) and CONTAIN! (monster negate).
  16. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon any fire monster from the GY. Link away the summoned fire monster + Promethean Princess to link summon Amblowhale.
  17. Activate Linkuriboh's effect to summon itself from the GY by tributing Poplar. 
  18. Link away Linkuriboh + Sunlight Wolf to link summon Heatsoul. Activate Heatsoul's effect to draw 1 card.
Rescue Ace may not have much negates, but the plethora of interruptions and the sheer advantage accrued by the deck wins many games. Next turn, you'll have so many cards in hand and follow-up in GY/field that you'll almost certainly OTK!
 
There are plenty of combos that fit particular situations, but the combo featured above is the mose optimal. Due to the number of starters it has, it can certainly play through handtraps/interruption, and if one strategy gets stopped, it can pivot to the other!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Snake-Eye Ash is the card you really want to resolve. Try to bait out your opponent's interruptions before you play this card.
  • If either a dark or fire is in the GY opponent's GY, (think Bystials or Ash Blossom), this deck can easily summon Dharc/Hiita so then they can link climb up to Promethean Princess!
  • Promethean Fire Princess may lock you into fire, but that's only when it's on the field! When you link her away for Amblowhale or another fire card, that's when you're free summon other monster attributes. 
  • Hydrant/Ash/Poplar can be linked away into Relinquished Anima! Opponents surprisingly leave many monsters vulnerable in the zones in front of the Extra Monster Zones, so when you have used Hydrant's effect to search, you may as well use it as a boardbreaker!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
The Rescue-ACE variant is quite possibly the best version of Snake-Eyes right now because of EMERGECY! consistency boost and Preventer's interruption/extension. Rescue-ACE Snake-Eye is my recommendation for your next ladder climb up the leagues Masterduel since it is consistent, can go 1st and 2nd, can play nicely into Maxx "C" and more!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description: star warrior new support test deck

The Chant of the Voice

This deck revolves around the powerful "Voiceless Voice" archetype, utilizing Light and Dark attributes to dominate the duel.

Core Strategy:

  • Ritual Focus: Multiple copies of "Pre-Preparation of Rites" and "Saffira, Queen of Dragons" enable consistent access to strong Fusion monsters like "Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice" and "Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended."
  • Hand Disruption & Protection: Hand traps like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring," "Effect Veiler," and "Infinite Impermanence" disrupt your opponent's plays, while "Called by the Grave" and "Crossout Designator" target specific threats.
  • Resource Management: "Pot of Prosperity" fuels your hand, while "Prayers of the Voiceless Voice" searches for archetype cards.

Key Cards:

  • Saffira Package: The core of the deck, with "Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice" offering high attack and negation, while "Sauravis, Dragon Sage of the Voiceless Voice" provides search and recursion.
  • Light Bringer Lucifer & Gyakutenno Megami: These powerful Light and Dark monsters enable Fusion Summons and offer additional effects.
  • Wingweaver: A versatile monster that can negate Spells/Traps or search for Ritual cards like "Advanced Ritual Art."

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck offers a toolbox of powerful Fusion monsters like "Saffira, Dragon Deity of the Voiceless Voice" and "Herald of the Arc Light" for various situations. Knightmare monsters provide removal options, while "Accesscode Talker" delivers high piercing damage.

Overall, this deck offers a powerful and consistent strategy with a focus on Fusion Summons and hand disruption. It utilizes the "Voiceless Voice" archetype's strong effects to control the field and overpower the opponent.

deck_excerpt: Competitive, Budget, Learning Curve, Midrange Deck.
deck_description:
Yup 7 URs and even with all the staples I've crafted these are still the boss monsters I go into, Simple things you need to know this deck is not Explosive or Too Slow its midrange no matter if go first or second you have plays to make.

Never be afraid to pop your cards you will get them back via Combo & Avarice. Outlast your opponent. 

Going down the list the Engine is only 21 cards the rest can be subbed out at you're leisure for cards like Maxx-C & Called By / Ash 

First the Engine 

Zoodiac Ratpier x1 , Zoodiac Bunnyblast x1 , Zoodiac Ramram x1 , Zoodiac Thoroughblade 3x , Zoodiac Whiptail x3. 

Fire Formation Tenki 3x , Zoodiac Barrage 3x , Zoodiac Combo x2 , Pot of Avarice x 3 , Foolish Burial Goods x1. 

Zoodiac Drident 1x , Zoodiac Tigermortar x 3 , Zoodiac Chakanine x3 , Zoodiac Boarbow 2x , Zoodiac Hammerkong 2x , Divine Arsenal AA Zeus 1x, Utopic Future 1x , Utopic Draco Future x1 , Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops 1x. 

___ 

 

Now for the Combo's , Key Terms | NS = Normal Summon , SS = Special Summon | Stack = SS Over said card | Pop : Destroy ( Target ) 

 ( Linear ) NS Any Zoo , Stack Boarbow , Stack Hammerkong , Stack Drident set whatever you have pass is your safest play against Nib. 

 ( Steps )

Step 1. Zoodiac Barrage Pop any NS Zoo , SS Ramram from deck. ( NS Thoroughblade & Discard Ramram works as well ) 

Step 2. Stack Chakanine onto Ramram, Use Chak to detach Ramram, SS Ramram. 

Step 3. Stack Drident onto Chak then detatch to Pop Ramram, Activate Ramram SS Chak 

Step 4. Stack Tigermortar onto Drident detatch then target Chak choose drident

Step 5. Use Chak and SS drident. 

Step 6. Use all 3 xyz Make Megaclops  or  Make Utopic Future over Tiger & Chak, Then Make Draco Future over Utopic ( only if you have Whiptail in hand to attatch to Drident )  

The most Important Notes : Zoodiac Boarbow can attack directly, Its your Easiest way to access Zeus, Zeus : He can detach 2 materials Send everything on field to graveyard you can make this guy have up to 6 Materials !

 

There's more stuff but you'll learn as you play, Good Luck on ladder.

Don't Forget to Craft :  Maxx "C" x 3 , Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3 , Called by The Grave x2. Buy the 750 Bundles in Store & Solo Mode for F2p Gems.

fun deck

This deck is a go second deck with a lot of tool box cards. Magical Musketeer has been a tier 3 and lower deck due to the sheer amount of power creep in the last decade. Its only strength is the spell/trap handtraps that interact with the opponent by negating cards, destroying face up cards, and banishing cards from grave. Its best matchup in the current format is stun since you can pick off fossil dyna more consistently than they can open judgment. (A testament of how slow a deck needs to be in order for the deck to dominate).

The Fiendsmith support provides the consistency that Musketeer has longed for because you can now search Caspar, Starfire or whatever Musketeer you need. Basically, you are now running 9 copies of Caspar/Starfire and 7 copies of Doc, Calamity, Wild and Kidbrave without taking up the deck space. You could run a similar Small World Package consisting of Ash, Effect Veiler and Nibiru as Small World bridges, but you always had to a) draw no Musketeers and b) needed one of the aforementioned drawn with Small World for the package to be worth it. Fiendsmith works as both a way to get to Starfire/Caspar and as a way to proc them. Its just an efficient searcher for Musketeers. Also, fi you are set on Musketeers, Lurrie is searched and dumped to become the second body needed to make Sequentia. 

The Fiendsmith combo lets your go first endboard be more than Caspar + Starfire pass, converting into Apollousa or High King Caesar with a Musketeer on board that can't be targeted. Prior to Fiendsmith, if you didn't open Caspar or Starfire going first, you were in a bad spot. Going second, if Max got negated, you just passed, now you can convert it into Fiendsmith stuff, making cards like Ash only stop the Musketeer side of the deck, requiring 2 negations minimum to stop the entire combo. Overall, the Fiendsmith engine is a welcome addition and should be run moving forward in every Musketeer deck.  

As for the the power cards of the deck, Super Poly, Link into the Vrains, and Ultimate Slayer all have the clause: your opponent cannot respond, making them 'guaranteed' against most meta decks. The idea is to ensure your Muskets can hit the field and these cards generate advantage through denying negation. Super Poly eats a minimum of 2 cards, Ultimate slayer does the same without the discard, and Link into the Vrains guarantees Max resolving his mass search effect or summon effect. If any of light fiend links get destroyed, it recurs 1 light fiend from grave (per copy of LITV). Also, it serves as an extender, so if you get Nibbed, you can just normal summon to continue your plays. 

Extra deck is running the bare minimum to do Musketeer and Fiendsmith combos because it works with the assumption you will just be shuffling everything back. If people start playing D.D. Crow in a format, bump ratios to 2 so you won't get stifled by a banished Lacrimosa or something. (That also means Super Poly or Ultimate Slayer will have to cut their engine size). Ultimate slayer runs the best of each summon type, allowing you to pop with N'tss, bounce with Malong, and negate with Aggregator. Garura is there because of the Super Poly Engine, but you can always just draw a card against fusion decks.   

Side deck can be tailered to the event you are going to, so this is by no means fixed. Run more s/t removal if your locals is all stun, run more anti Snake-eyes (or whatever is tier 1) cards if you are going to a YCS. Make adjustments to have a better matchup against the most popular decks. 

Final Notes: 

Runick Fiendsmith Musket is a build I was contemplating but after thorough testing with Runick Muskets in TCG and MD, there are far too many weaknesses to warrant running it with Fiendsmith Musket. You cut Musket S/t to 1 make space for Runick cards, the power cards are (unsurprisingly) more powerful than any of the Runicks, the draw 3 effect of Fountain requires you to draw into Runicks to keep that engine going, and the no BP clause makes the game artifically longer. If Fountain never goes up OR if it goes down, Runick stops working on your opponent's turn. Fiendsmith puts up a lot of damage on board on behalf of the otherwise weak Musketeers, so you can close out games quicker with the non Runick variant. Quicker games, means you grind less in every game, and mitigate the risk of going into time. Also longer games take its toll on you as a player for 9+ round events.

deck_name: All Hands on deck for the Skill Drain Event
deck_excerpt: A fun little realtively cheap deck for the Extreme Duel Skill Drain.
deck_description:
A Quick description of why every card is included:

Battle Fader : Ends the battle phase if you get attacked directly. Pairs well with skill drain, cause no pierce.

Swift Scarecrow : Does the same as Battle Fader only better, since it doesn't leave a body on the field.

Magic Hand : By far the worst card in the deck and only in here because of the hands theme. Replace with any other card if you don't need maximum hands.

Fire Hand : Destroys a monster on destruction and summons an Ice Hand . It needs something to destroy to summon though. NOT once per turn, so if their board is full and you got some life points crash, destroy monster, summon ice, crash, destroy spell/trap, summon fire, crash ...

Ice Hand : Destroys a spell/trap on destruction and summons a Fire Hand . It needs something to destroy to summon though. NOT once per turn, so if their board is full and you got some life points crash, destroy spell/trap, summon fire, crash, destroy monster, summon ice, crash ...

Prominence Hand : Probably the second worst card in the deck, but fairly useful to go into XYZs.

Thunder Hand : Basically a hand trap that triggers on a destruction of a Magic Hand , Fire Hand  or Ice Hand and destroys something while summoning itself.

Lord of the Heavenly Prison : Protects your set cards. If you already have an Imperial Iron Wall going you can set anything and it won't get banished.

Pot of Avarice : Recycles your hands and draws stuff.

Pot of Extravagance : You don't really need your extra deck, draw stuff instead.

Pot of Prosperity :: You don't really need your extra deck, draw stuff instead.

Cauldron of the Old Man : Funnily a real problem for most decks here. Your main win condition.

Waboku : Dying is harder if you don't take battle damage.

Draining Shield : Quick heal, can be replaced.

Threatening Roar : You can't take battle damage if your opponent can't attack.

Rainbow Life : I have a soft spot for that card. It really isn't that good and the discard is kinda costly, but I just like that card for some reason. Can be replaced, since SR is kinda costly for what it actually does.

Imperial Iron Wall : Just a fun addition to be able to search anything with Lord of the Heavenly Prison , sadly deactivates 2 of the pots.

 

Except for the 2 Number 106: Giant Hand  in the extra decks every monster is either a beatstick or a wall.

deck_excerpt: Pure Vaal deck post infinite forbidden
deck_description: Runs pure, could add some other synchros or level four stuff but is a good basis for otking and safely building with cross out. Not a lot to fit as the vaal cards can take a lot, but I think the consistency and adaptablility is strong as long as they maintain through hand traps.

Side Deck Not Included.

 

Going First:

Find a way to link into Folgo, Justice Fur Hire, get a way to destroy cards on your opponent's turn such as Donpa, Marksman Fur Hire on field & Rex, Freight Fur Hire in GY, get 2 "Fur Hire"s alongside Folgo on the field to draw 3 cards, and get as many hand traps as possible to basically stop your opponent from playing the game. Alternative options are Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, Rafale, Champion Fur Hire, & Wiz, Sage Fur Hire for negates.

54.27% chance to open at least 1 hand trap, starter, & "Fur Hire"s to summon according to the yugioh.party calculator

Going Second:

Link climb to Borrelsword Dragon, Borreload Dragon, and/or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax to end the game or at the very least deal some damage. If you open enough hand traps you can interrupt your opponent which should make this easier. The odds you draw at least two hand traps are pretty high so it's likely you will have interruptions.

68.44% chance to open at least 1 hand trap, starter, & "Fur Hire"s to summon according to the yugioh.party calculator

Other Tools:

There are some neat non-engine tools such as:

Archnemeses Eschatos, which isn't searchable, but when you draw it it's not hard for Fur Hires to summon it and it can be detrimental to decks that rely on one type of monster (i.e HEROs).

I:P Masquerena, Anybody who plays anything competitive knows what this generic link-2 does and it's very self-explanatory, same with Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, which if you go full combo into has 3-4 negates with Falgo on field.

Knightmare Unicorn, Knightmare Phoenix, & Knightmare Cerberus, generic toolbox cards that have uses. Phoenix destroys backrow, Cerberus destroys monsters, and Unicorn shuffles monsters back into the deck.

 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy & Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze are primarily used to steal monsters from the graveyard. Unfortunately this build does not run any search targets for Hiita, and only one for Dharc, if you want to play targets and stay Fur Hire, you can run Bravo, Fighter Fur Hire for Hiita and more copies of Seal, Strategist Fur Hire for Dharc. Or you can play other out-of-archetype targets.

deck_excerpt: Guess what will come out of this hat
deck_description:
Skeleton for a trap monster deck. Uses a few monsters that special themselves to get into Top Hat Hare and grab the trap that's missing from your hand, Extrav & Morganite for draw power and extra recovery. The main cast is Anguish that makes every other trap monster summon after it a pop 1, Azurune negates special summons by sending another trap mon, Tiki Soul protects the rest & Tiki Curse helps in battle, Jirai Gumo is a conditional pop 1 by itself, Silhouhatte & Apophis negate monsters, Shapesister is a tuner giving access to synchros, Metamorphortress can convert a spare Red Layer into a 3k beater.

The alternatives include Hamon for a beating, an Eldlich engine, an illusion engine for the thematic-ness, Kiriban & BBS to get her or any other monster, Sanctum protects set backrow on the field, Trap Gather is funny, Magic Planter could be a neat option, Critias could be fun to mess around with as a side thing, Thrust can grab your spells or paleos, Anguish pops on either field so an Artifact engine is valid, Stungray is another monster, as is Metal Reflect Slime which can convert into Egyptian God Slime, and as hinted Paleozoic is also a neat engine to splice.
This is an updated version of the dinosaur deck I want to get.

deck_description: Testing
Don't mind the deck list you see while scrolling cause I put in some new cards so will edit this soon

Trying to make Pure Harpies as consistent and competitve as possible, and I think I did a pretty decent job. Small World helps a lot with getting channeler as often as possible. Trap Trick, which probably should be at 3 copies (swap for 1 Hysteric Party or 1 Small World), is to help get Feather Storm as often as possible, as it is the card that wins you most of your games because of its insane negate effect.

All of the hand traps, aside from Nibiru, that I chose work with Small world since they all only share 1 Type/Attr/Lvl/ATK/DEF with any of the Harpies. So, you can banish the hand trap from your deck to get to channeler. Nibiru is kind of insane with Cyber Slash and could probably be main decked, because you can just bounce the token on the following turn and go in for game, but opted for Droll and Lock Bird for going first. For the extra deck, I don't actually have S:P but if I did I would run it. If you don't have S:P, I would maybe run either Knightmare Unicorn or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax (which is what I am running).

deck_excerpt: Fire fist your opponent to dust or drop them into the abyss with your Traprrix
deck_description:
This isn't a description, deal with it (this is a technically playable fire fist traptrix deck for HAT format, based on the list used by 

ghostmourner)
Cute Big Animal Warriors
Budget Tenpai Dragon
I need these card ( all the Kuriboh are plain card)
My childhood deck

Utilizing scrap recycler's non opt foolish burial effect, you can set up some of the most impressive orcut boards since TOSS format. Using the horus engine gives the deck the ability to protect itself from handtraps and extend through opponents interaction. It also allows you to send drawn orcust combo pieces from your hand to the graveyard so you can activate their graveyard effects. Also, I would definitely cut 3x scrapyard. its an okay starter but you don't need fossil dig and scrapyard since they do the exact same thing.

Cheapest Tenpai/Sangen deck I could make without butchering the whole thing. This is a great blind second OTK deck, even with prosperity.

Main combo:

Activate Sangen Summoning, add Tenpai Dragon Paidra

Normal Summon Paidra, add Sangen Kaimen

- Battle Phase -

Activate Sangen Kaimen, add and Special Summon Chundra

Attack with Paidra (even if your opponent's monster has higher ATK; it won't be destroyed due to Paidra's effect.) and activate Chundra's effect to Special Summon Fadra

Attack with all monsters (if available)

Paidra Quick Effect to Synchro with Chundra into Bident (Or other Synchros if needed)

Bident Synchro Summon effect to Summon back Chundra

Attack more, activate Fadra to Special Summon back the Paidra

Fadra Quick Effect to Synchro into Transcendent using Bident

Activate Bident to Summon itself

Attack more (again)...

From here, you can make Hieratic Seals and Summon back Transcendent, or Synchro into other guys...

With most combos, you should be able to OTK pretty much every time, except for a few very specific situations in which your opponent is floodgating you.

Note: To deal a bunch of damage, you can also make Kuibelt, destroy the Field Spell and double its ATK.

Enjoy!

deck_description: The set Raging God of the Sea is a Secret Pack, released on April 24th, 2024. Today I will introduce to you a deck that was introduced in this secret pack. This is an easy to play and quite cheap deck that hopes to help you have more entertaining decks. Below is the deckprofile for everyone's reference.

Destroy your own cards with Kuraz the Light Monarch's effect to draw more cards! Destroying Geartown with Kuraz and Ancient Fairy Dragon will trigger the field spell's effect!
